post_text: School Board votes (6 to 2) to uphold face-to-face plan for families who selected it. For more than five hours, Orange County School Board members held public comment and discussion on the recommendations from the Medical Advisory Committee and any potential revisions to the OCPS 2020-2021 Optional Reopening Innovative Plan. After thoughtful discussion, the school board voted to uphold the previous plan that was approved last month. For families who selected face-to-face instruction, students will attend school in-person beginning Friday, Aug. 21. Families who selected LaunchEd@Home will continue with LaunchEd@Home. All of the health and safety measures that have been put in place will proceed as planned with extra vigilance. Health and Safety Procedures Manual is linked here. https://www.ocps.net/UserFiles/Servers/Server_54619/File/Students%20and%20Parents/School%20Reopening%202020/COVID-19%20Health%20and%20Safety%20Manual.pdf

Starting today, Aug. 10, OCPS Food and Nutrition Services will provide meals for students utilizing the LaunchEd@Home instructional model with a Curbside Meals Program. The meals will be available on Mondays at all 202 OCPS schools for LaunchEd@Home students. The entire week of meals can be picked up every Monday starting 30 minutes after dismissal and will be served for an hour and a half.

Students picking up meals must provide a student ID, and if parents are coming through the lines, they must provide their student‚Äôs name and ID number. This is needed because students will use their current meal benefit status (free, reduced or paid). Tax-free shopping is this weekend! The 2020 Back-to-School Sales Tax Holiday begins on Friday, August 7, 2020, and ends on Sunday, August 9, 2020.

During this sales tax holiday period, qualifying items will be exempt from tax, including certain school supplies selling for $15 or less per item; clothing, footwear, and certain accessories selling for $60 or less per item; and the first $1,000 of the sales price of personal computers and certain computer-related accessories purchased for noncommercial home or personal use. More info here: https://revenuelaw.floridarevenue.com/LawLibraryDocuments/2020/06/TIP-123084_TIP_20A01-04_FINAL_RLL.pdf

Here is a comparison of the three instructional models that parents can choose from for the fall semester, which will tentatively start Friday, August 21.

Parents/guardians are asked to register your choice for your child for the fall semester for the 2020-2021 school year. Your selection registers your child for your choice of instructional model. The choices are Face-to-Face as required by the state, Orange County Virtual School or OCPS LaunchED@Home. To review each model and register, go to https://bit.ly/ocpsreopening.

To maximize safety efforts, we *strongly* encourage selecting the OCPS LaunchED@Home, if you are able to keep your child at home.

If you have questions, there is a link to FAQs on the reopening page. The Choice Registration Form is now available and will be open until Friday, July 24. If the registration process is not completed by July 24, the student will be registered to attend their zoned or assigned school utilizing the Face-to-Face instructional model.

OCPS parents, as the School Board prepares to consider plans for reopening schools, we want to encourage you to review three options for your child. On the front page of ocps.net there is a School Reopening graphic that will take you to a description of the choices so you can begin considering which is best for your family. This will help to clarify the options that were discussed last Tuesday.

The options include:

1) face-to-face five days a week as required by the state;

2) Orange County Virtual School, an existing option that has been in place for years;

or

3) a potential innovative model that requires state approval once the school board votes on the plan next Tuesday.

If and when the state approves an innovative plan there will be an on-line registration to select a model for your child for the 2020-21 fall semester which ends in December. We will send an update after the board meeting on Tuesday.

Thank you for working with us during these challenging times.

(See comments for this information in Spanish, Haitian-Creole and Portuguese.)

Per the direction of Dr. Pino with the Florida Health Department - Orange County, Dr. Jenkins made this announcement last night to our families of 2020 graduates.

"I want to again congratulate you and your children of this notable accomplishment. I know our students will go on to accomplish great things. As promised, I am calling to give you the final decision regarding in-person graduation ceremonies. I am sure you are aware of the increasing number of COVID-19 cases in Orange County. After consulting with Dr. Pino of the Health Department, and based upon his expert guidance, I am sad to announce that there will be no in-person graduation ceremonies for the class of 2020. I want to thank you for your patience and support during these unprecedented times. We wish your senior all the best and a promising future filled with success."
- Superintendent Barbara Jenkins

post_text: Florida Department of Education Commissioner Richard Corcoran issued an Emergency Order this afternoon pertaining to the reopening of schools. To view the executive order click here http://www.fldoe.org/core/fileparse.php/19861/urlt/DOE-2020-EO-06.pdf The School Board will meet as scheduled for its work session Tuesday, July 7, at noon, to discuss reopening of schools in Orange County. The meeting will be carried live on the board meeting YouTube channel. In June, we solicited ideas from families, employees and the community through an online Think Tank. Thousands shared their ideas to consider for our return to school. The input was screened and reviewed by four workgroups made up of administrators, teachers, union members and staff. Their summaries are available online as are the more than 6,000 ideas and comments submitted to the Think Tank. This year, as an AP student at West Orange High School - OCPS, he tutored other students, studied during breaks at track meets, played in the school‚Äôs top Jazz Band and earned a QuestBridge scholarship to Vanderbilt University. He plans to study computer science and knows that being a 19-year old graduate, or a ‚Äúsenior citizen‚Äù as he calls himself, gives him the resilience, humility and purpose he needs to push himself toward more success in his life. https://youtu.be/P-xVQpLzLik

post_text:
OCPS is looking ahead to the 2020-21 school year. While Florida districts are waiting for direction from the Governor and Florida Department of Education regarding reopening, OCPS is brainstorming now for three potential models: (1) distance learning, (2) face-to-face learning, and (3) blended distance and face-to-face learning.

We invite you to be a part of our School Reopening Think Tank by submitting ideas here: bit.ly/OCPSreopening. We want suggestions related to the three potential school reopening models. Your responses will be reviewed by staff and labor union representatives in our reopening work groups. They will brainstorm best ideas for consideration.

post_text: OCPS parents: while no decision has been made about what next school year will look like, we do know many of you have had inquiries and questions about virtual school options for your child. You may not be aware but Orange County Public Schools has run its own virtual school for ten years. Orange County Virtual School is an option for full and part-time instruction for all students kindergarten through 12th grade. If you are wondering if Orange County Virtual is right for your child, there is a lot of information on their website, where you will find a message from the principal, answers to frequently asked questions, and how to attend virtual information sessions. Just go to OCVS.ocps.net to learn more about the opportunities offered by Orange County Virtual School.

You may not be aware but Orange County Public Schools has run its own virtual school for ten years. Orange County Virtual School is an option for full and part-time instruction for all students kindergarten through 12th grade. If you are wondering if Orange County Virtual is right for your child, there is a lot of information on their website, where you will find a message from the principal, answers to frequently asked questions, and how to attend virtual information sessions. Just go to OCVS.ocps.net to learn more about the opportunities offered by Orange County Virtual School.

OCPS is partnering with the University of Central Florida to provide educational programming on public channel WUCF TV. This includes television programming tied to educational standards for school-aged children from OCPS teachers along with supplemental content provided by WUCF. The series of videos are geared toward children in kindergarten through second grade, and will complement the workbook materials that all K-2 OCPS students are receiving in the mail for summer enrichment.

Here is a sample lesson (https://bit.ly/2XodjiK) and here is how to access channel 24.5 (https://bit.ly/36VwF1Q).

post_text:
Today, as our community and our nation grapples with so many difficult, but important, challenges, as Pride Month begins, and as the anniversary of the Pulse tragedy approaches, we lift up the harmony of our diverse and culturally-rich #OCPSArts students in song. Created in 2016 and dedicated to everyone affected by the shooting at Pulse, we rededicate this performance of ‚ÄúBeautiful City‚Äù to our community, and rededicate ourselves to ensuring every student has a promising and successful future.

Out of the ruins and rubble
Out of the smoke
Out of our night of struggle
Can we see a ray of hope?
One pale thin ray reaching for the day
We can build a beautiful city
Yes, we can; yes, we can
We can build a beautiful city
Not a city of angels but we can build a city of man.

-From the musical "Godspell"
Arrangement by Mac Huff
Videography by Diacom

post_text: Orange County Public Schools was the recipient of a generous donation that is helping to provide a safe environment for school employees and others working at the 52 school sites distributing meals for children. Guang Ming Temple donated 6,000 disposable face masks for staff to wear while they are handing out meals to families in the drive-thru style process. The masks help protect employees and anyone they come in contact with during the meal distribution. District employees are required to wear the face masks at all times when working with the public.

post_text:
More for #TeacherAppreciationWeek: 8,500 thank you letters from the #Classof2020 will be delivered to OCPS teachers as part of #ProjectImpact. For the past 4 years, we've delivered many in person, and while that's not possible this year, the sentiment that comes through in these letters is still palpable. Here are two examples, one from a senior at Jones High School - OCPS to Mr. Wille at Howard Middle School Academy of Arts-OCPS and another from a senior at Windermere High School, Orange County Public Schools to Mr. Sellers at Bridgewater Middle School - OCPS.

You'll see more of these letters this week. If you're the parent of a senior, ask which teacher they chose and why!

And for *even* more on #TeacherAppreciationWeek, check out the #OCPSHeroTeacher campaign on our Twitter feed at https://twitter.com/ocpsnews.

post_text:
To celebrate #TeacherAppreciationWeek, the High School Division organizes #ProjectImpact. Now in its 4th year, this is a way for graduating seniors to thank an elementary or middle school teacher who impacted their life. Normally, 100 of these letters would be hand delivered by the superintendent, school board members or other district leaders. This year, the teachers will receive the letter a former student wrote, along with a video of someone reading the letter to them. Within the next few weeks, 8,500 letters will be sent to the OCPS teachers these students chose.

Today‚Äôs spotlight is a letter to Stone Lakes Elementary teacher Mary Ellington. Senior Stephen Claydon says she inspired him to have confidence in himself and what he is capable of accomplishing. That confidence will serve him well next year, as he will attend the United States Air Force Academy.

A School Board Meeting will be held today, Tuesday at 5:30 p.m. The meeting will be live streamed at the following link: https://www.youtube.com/user/OCPSboardmeetings.

Members of the public who wish to provide public comment may call (407) 250-6270. Callers may get into the calling queue from 5:15 p.m. to 5:30 p.m. and public comment will be taken as the School Board goes through the agenda. You can find the agenda on the School Board section of the website at www.ocps.net

Speakers may also address the School Board during the 4:30 p.m. pre-agenda meeting using the same call-in information. Those comments that are related to the work of the School Board; not specific to the 5:30 p.m. agenda.

More sad news for our student-athletes, especially our seniors, but health and safety always come first.

From the Florida High School Athletic Association: "It is with heavy hearts that the FHSAA has decided to cancel all FHSAA affiliated events, inclusive of the state series and all championship events, for spring sports. The safety of our student-athletes, coaches, officials, and fans is our top priority. With the evolving threat of the CORONAVIRUS (COVID-19), we must ensure that we do not contribute to the spread of this illness. We are deeply saddened for our student-athletes who have seen their seasons and/or high school careers end so abruptly. Our Association knows the impact and role high school athletics play
in the lives of so many and will continue to work towards the betterment of high school sports. We know this is a trying time, but the health and safety of all is of utmost importance to this Association."

post_text:
Dear OCPS Class of 2020 and parents,

We know this has been a difficult time of uncertainty for our seniors. As a result of the governor‚Äôs ‚ÄúSafe-at-Home‚Äù order and schools being closed through at least May 1, graduation ceremonies for all of our high schools have been postponed.

The governor said in his press conference today that he is not ready to announce a return to school date. His decision is critical to our plans. The superintendent has engaged her student advisory council, and high school principals have received input from their student government representatives regarding options such as smaller ceremonies in school auditoriums or football stadiums. They have even considered virtual ceremonies. In the superintendent's discussions with students, she has heard their disappointment but also witnessed their resilience.

We will announce final graduation plans to recognize our amazing seniors as soon as possible. At this point, we believe they may be delayed until June or July. We will provide updates as they become available.

Please stay safe.

#OCPSDistanceAssistance Safety is our top priority when students are learning in school or at a distance. Parents, help us encourage online safety for students by:

a) Using sites that protect student information. Look for sites that start with an https//: like LaunchPad

b) Requiring students to be signed in to the Chrome browser using their OCPS student account

c) Use technology in open common spaces, if possible, never allow video conferencing behind closed doors,

and d) Discuss the difference between personal vs. private information with students and remind them to keep passwords private.

Pop on over to the Distance Assistance page at DistanceLearning.ocps.net for more online safety tips!

2020 AP Exams will be:

‚è± 45 minutes long
üìñ Open book/open note
üíªOnline (or a photo of handwritten work)

OCPS is an open access district, so we pay for all students to take the exam. We strongly encourage all students to try the free-response exam for each course since a passing score can help save money in college.

OCPS families, we know many in our community are struggling as a result of COVID-19. This is a tough situation for us all, whether you're dealing with a sick family member, have young children who don't understand what's happening or a senior who's missing out on some of the most important milestones in their young lives, many of us are feeling overwhelmed. If you need help, *please* reach out. There are many resources available for residents from Orange County, Florida Government.

For mental health help in dealing with COVID-19 stress, call 211 for a referral. Orange County has listed many more resources available on their website at https://www.orangecountyfl.net/EmergencySafety/Coronavirus/Coronavirus-ResidentResources.aspx#.XoUQV4hKhPY.

OCPS Mental Health Services Department has resources listed too: https://ocps.instructure.com/courses/1168604/pages/resources-for-families

And let's all make sure to be kind to one another during this stressful time. We're #allinthistogether.

post_text: The health and safety of our community comes first, but it's hard to see our students miss out on important milestone opportunities in their young lives. The closures mean missed field trips and proms. Students worked very hard to prepare for concert performances, robotics competitions and spring musicals. Many athletes have also seen their dreams put on hold. The Orlando Sentinel profiled one story, that of Edgewater High‚Äôs Christian Leary. https://www.orlandosentinel.com/coronavirus/os-sp-coronavirus-christian-leary-0324-20200324-i6xjmnpqfnhp3cfc6mb3d7bbcm-story.html
shared_text:
ORLANDOSENTINEL.COM
Coronavirus puts brakes on Edgewater speedster Christian Leary
text:
The health and safety of our community comes first, but it's hard to see our students miss out on important milestone opportunities in their young lives. The closures mean missed field trips and proms. Students worked very hard to prepare for concert performances, robotics competitions and spring musicals. Many athletes have also seen their dreams put on hold. The Orlando Sentinel profiled one story, that of Edgewater High‚Äôs Christian Leary. https://www.orlandosentinel.com/coronavirus/os-sp-coronavirus-christian-leary-0324-20200324-i6xjmnpqfnhp3cfc6mb3d7bbcm-story.html

post_text:
OCPS families, we have disappointing news to share. Following the recommendations of the CDC and the Florida Department of Health about social gatherings, along with cancellations by some venues, the district made the difficult decision to cancel all proms and Grad Bash events. Refunds will be processed for tickets purchased for these events.

NO decision has been made in regards to graduation ceremonies. We are hopeful that we will be able hold our regularly scheduled graduations at the end of the year. This decision will be made in the coming weeks as we continue to monitor the situation daily.

We know how important events like these are to students and families. Our principals and teachers, indeed all of us, are very proud of our students and the hard work they put forward this year. As distance learning begins next week, our schools are committed to ensuring students finish the year strong.

This is an unprecedented time in our lives. Our students will be remembered for their resilience and grace during this challenging time for our nation. Thank you for your continued support.

The parade, nearly 25 cars long, honked and waved to show their "wolf pups" how much they are missed, while still adhering to social distancing protocols. Parents were given the heads up on this surprise so they could bring their children out to their driveways or watch through their windows.

post_text:
Governor DeSantis and the Florida Department of Education just held a conference call with all of the state superintendents. The following updates have been made:

1. Students will not return to campus until Wednesday, April 15th.

2. All statewide assessments have been cancelled this school year.

3. There will be no school grades released for the 2019-2020 school year. *(As in the school grade the Florida Department of Education assigns a school. Thus, there will be no district grade as well.)

More information and details to follow. Please stay tuned.
